6. Overlay: This allows containers on different physical hosts to communicate as if they were on the same network. Itâ€™s used primarily with Docker Swarm 7. None: This is total isolation. The container has no external network access, just a loopback interface. It's useful

communication across the subnet without needing special switch support.IPvlan L3: Containers get IPs from a different subnet, and the host acts as their router. For communication to the outside world, you need to configure a static route on your router pointing to the host.

Think of it like plugging multiple MACs into a single switch port, your switch needs special handling to make sense of that.5. IPvlan (L2 & L3): IPvlan comes in two modes:IPvlan L2: Similar to Macvlan, but all containers share the hostâ€™s MAC address. Itâ€™s simpler and allows

4. Macvlan: This works at Layer 2 (Data Link). Each container gets its own MAC and IP address from the local network, almost like a separate physical machine. However, containers canâ€™t easily talk to the host or other containers unless you enable promiscuous mode.

3. Host: As the name implies, the container shares the hostâ€™s network stack. It uses the hostâ€™s IP directly, no NAT, no port mapping. It behaves like a process running natively on the host. Great for performance, but you lose network isolation.

but for external communication, you need to map ports explicitly.2. User-defined Bridge: Very similar to the default bridge, except you create and manage the network yourself. One advantage is that containers in a user-defined bridge can communicate by name.

Docker provides seven types of networks, each designed for specific use cases:1. Default Bridge: This is Dockerâ€™s default network. When you spin up a container without specifying a network, it gets attached to this bridge. Containers can talk to each other using IP addresses,

Most DevOps engineers donâ€™t spend much time thinking about Docker networking, but I think itâ€™s a cool and underrated topic. Understanding how your containers communicate under the hood helps your troubleshooting skills and gives you more control over your deployments.
